◊small-topic{Alexander Nabavi-Noori}

◊image-aside["images/Xander_Color.jpg"]

I am a first-year Ph.D. student and Ashford Fellow in Government and Social Policy at ◊link["https://www.gov.harvard.edu/people/graduate-students/" "Harvard University,"] and an affiliate of the ◊link["https://caps.gov.harvard.edu/" "Center for American Political Studies."] My ◊xref["research.html" "research"] examines how legal regimes build, reshape, and constrain American political institutions, particularly the federal bureaucracy and Congress. 

I came to graduate study by way of law, after working in various roles across the federal government: in the executive branch, on Capitol Hill, and in the federal judiciary. Those experiences drew me to questions about how institutions actually work. Much of what institutions do—and how well they do it—turns on things legal categories do not always capture: the motivations and limitations of the people inside them, the organizational cultures that form around them, and the informal practices through which formal authority is exercised. To that end, I'm interested in the ◊link["colophon.html#other" "humanness of the state."]

Outside of research, I enjoy yoga, drinking more coffee than I should, and spending plenty of time at bookstores. I am also interested in typography and design—this site being one small outlet for those interests (see the ◊xref["colophon.html" "colophon"])—and am an avid follower of consumer technology.